segments.text: You were saying the things that got us into that situation.
The things that got us into those situations, I think, are a breakdown in some of those qualities of leadership that I spoke about earlier.
Integrity, openness, integrity, and...

qualities of advisors it's just you know if if if those qualities had been as they should have been I don't think we'd had those things Watergate for instance I don't think well in first place it was bad judgment and judgment is a great part of leadership it was bad judgment initially

it was integrity and honesty with the people that the president covered up what he did i'm not a expert politician but i think looking back on it had the president immediately said what happened opened up the files and said you know we made a mistake wipe it off i think it would have blown away but
You know, there's nobody good enough liar to tell the same story over and over and keep it going.
Yeah, right.
And I'll tell you, he did that.

Of course, there was a lot more to it than that, but, you know, you can just see faults of leadership all the way up and down the line that causes political crisis, military crisis, or crisis in the highway department, any of them, any crisis.
Yeah, right.
Let's...
Do you have any other thoughts that you'd like to express on leadership before we turn to another topic?
Well, I'd just say this.
There is no substitute for leadership.
There is no substitute.
There's people that can succeed with one kind of leadership, as we said, another kind of leadership, and you've got one kind and I've got another.
But you've got to have some quality of leadership, or you will go under.
Your people will not respect you.
And the many people who do not respect you, well, then you've got disaster.
So I'll just sum it up.
The importance of leadership is that it's an absolute must, or you're not going to succeed.
Simple.
Let's turn now.
to Texas A&M.
Back to Texas A&M, we talked about Texas A&M back in the 1930's when you were here.
There have been some major changes at this institution since that time and I'd like your thoughts as a former student on the changes that came about at this university, especially in the 1960's.
What are your thoughts on
The end of the mandatory Corps of Cadets.
Well, I think I could answer that this way.
I think that we ought to have mandatory military training nationwide.
I think everybody ought to serve some responsibility for the defense of this country.
I think we're, whatever you call it,
mandatory military or mandatory training.
I think everybody ought to have some training in military, hospital, or some part of the welfare and defense of this country.
Could you develop that?
For a short time.
How short?
Oh, maybe a year, 18 months.

are something to get his foot in the door of knowing the responsibility, knowing the needs of defense, knowing the needs of the country, and above that, somebody knowing what his capabilities are, and have a record of him.
This business of turning everybody loose and then have to go back and re...

register and all this i think that's a wheel spinning i think it's a waste and i think it leads to unpreparedness so my thinking of that i think there should be if you if it's a military school i think you ought to have if you're physically capable i would i saw nothing wrong with
having mandatory ROTC, two years.
If people don't care for that any longer, then they go into the civilian.
That would be like 18 months or a year or whatever outside.
But I think where there's that privilege, anybody that doesn't take the opportunity of it, I think they're missing a great deal.
Were you sorry then to see the university shift away from the mandatory report?
Yes.
And I know why they did it.
You know, it was not popular.
And I'm sure that it would have run off a lot of students.
But, you know, I think maybe more schools should have it.
I think it would not hurt to have a basic understanding of military responsibility.
Because as far as you and I are sitting here, some of these days we may need it, or will need it, most likely.
No, you said everybody.
Are you including women?
I don't see anything wrong with that.
There would probably be more women that might have deferments or some such thing as that, but there still could be places of service.
But I really can't see a great deal of difference.
Depending on their marital status or their responsibility status or whatever, you know, the ladies have said that they want equal opportunities.
I don't know why that shouldn't be one of them.
I was not a bit sorry to see them integrated into the service.
You could get a place.
Now, let's talk about that for a minute.
Did you have women under your command?
They were just coming into the service.
We had a few at that time, but it was not very prevalent at that time.
How were they accepted?
Oh, there was some reluctance, but, you know, the job they could do is as well as men.
And I think it depends entirely upon their attitude because they have job skills just as in the civilian market.
There are things that women do to exceed men.
So, but it was slow.
It was a thing that was, you know, they had to get used to.
You told me two days ago, I believe, that you had
In the 420th, did you say 4,500 men and officers?
At one time.
At one time.
How many of those were women?
Very few.
Half a dozen?
I doubt if there were very many more than that.
It was just a very few, and at this point I really don't remember.
But they were just not significant at all.
because see this was in 1971.
Yeah.
But uh- Did you recruit for women?
I don't believe we did at that time.
Had not and I guess they do now.
And why didn't you?
Because you had plenty of men.
Well that's one thing we never were even up to the time I retired we we had not we did not have
personnel problems in that respect.
In fact, as I told you the other day, we had waiting lists.
In fact, we had to keep a very well-oriented and well-run waiting list so that we could substantiate those that we took in.
But I've always had a feeling that
I'll let the person do the job that's best qualified regardless of their status in life, whether it's man, woman, or what.
Now, speaking of women, what were your feelings when A&M allowed women
You went to an all-male institution back in the 1930s, and now it's the freshman class is 51% women.
What were your feelings about allowing women?
I thought it was one of the smartest things they ever did.
Why?
Why is that?
Well, because at first it's a tax-supported institution, and there are women who want to go to school,
I think it, in my opinion, it enhanced even enrollment of men.
There were a lot of people that would not go to an all-male school, and I'm sure the same as to an all-women's school.
But, well, it just made sense.
Why exclude any one gender?
The school was there.
They had the facilities.
They had the capability.
And in addition to that, I had a daughter that I wanted to go to school with.
But I really thought that was a landmark decision.
I was tickled to death.
And I know that a lot of my colleagues don't agree with that.
I'm talking about my vintage.
In fact, I've had some
My classmates say that Mr.
Rudder was the downfall of any university because this happened under his rule, but I've had some very strong arguments with him that I think it put the place on an upward course.
Oh, I thought he was great.
I think I can predict this, but what do you think about racial integration that came about under General Rudder?
There ain't nothing wrong with that either.
Of course, over the last three interviews, you've sort of seen my feeling toward the black race particularly.
And we just use all races.
But the black race is the one that's mostly in controversy.
But if they're academically qualified and have the intention to go,
Well, that's like the women were.
They were just as entitled to go as I was.
There was tremendous growth.
There were about, I think, 4,000 students when you were here in 1940, about that.
Right about that.
And as late as 1960, there were only around 6,000, 7,000, and now there's 31,000.
What have you thought about this incredible growth that we've had?
I don't understand it.
Except that I think that it's a further mark of the quality of the institution.
We were growing when other institutions had leveled off.
And I have heard, well, one in particular, Dr. Williams, other than Mr. Rutter, say that we had been visited by people, administrators from other institutions, to find out what the recipe was.
And I'm not sure they could tell them, other than these things that I've talked about, the quality of the institution,
The openness of the administration, and the fact that the school's got a great reputation, and the fact that they finally saw fit to open it up to ladies, all races, and whatnot.
But it's, I think, mainly it's the quality of the institution.
I like to think that.
Now let's talk about General Rudder.
It was during his tenure in office that these changes took place.
When did you first meet him?
Well, I met him several times in the reserve program prior to his assuming the presidency of A&M in mutual reserve meetings and exercises and whatnot.
but not really on a personal basis until about the time that he came to A&M.
And I got better acquainted with him just by the fact that he was in town.

But when I really got acquainted with him is, as I assumed, more responsibility in the highway department, because we had a great many mutual problems, highway department, university, with all their lands.
and roads that were built in and around and through.
And then his...
So you were cooperating then with the president?
And your district were cooperating to build roads?
Sure.
See, we, under my administration, we built Jersey Street, you know, right across the campus.
We built the highway that's on the

south side of the campus along with the railroad we built the underpass out there by the agriculture building and we widened and expanded jersey street i mean uh university drive we extended university drive back to the east expanded highway six you know just all around and through as well as the west loop
the west loop around town entailed a great bit of university property.
So I dealt with him on many very intricate and detailed planning of roads and facilities in and around the stadium and the university tubes.
So would you explain how it worked?
Would he take care of the roads inside the campus and you take, or how did it work?
How was the relationship?

Well, in a time that we had any plans for expansion or improvement adjacent to the campus or through any of the lands of the campus, some of it even had to go to the Board of Regents for approval because we got some land from them for the West Loop, for instance, and the Jersey Street.
We took part of the lands of the university and he had to
clear this through the Board of Regents.

So as we would plan these facilities, we would work closely with him to get his ideas and input into how it could serve and what would be the best facility and where it ought to be and this sort of thing.
And then, of course, we built it, but it was done with mutual coordination.
Whose funds?
Highway Department.
Highway Department.
They did not put any funds

into any of the roads that we built in and around the university and where we had some of their lands it was it was donated to to the highway department to build roads on but it was highway funds which are some state and some federal when people work with other people it's usually rather easy to work with them and they're very cooperative when you're going to do something for them
But when you're not going to do something for him, then things often change.
What kind of man was General Rutter when you told him that you couldn't do something that he wanted accomplished?
Well, he would immediately say, go back and think about it.
I remember a very, very specific problem that we had that we
We resolved, but it was not to his liking.
And here again, I think that takes leadership.
If I want you to do something that you don't want to do or you resist, it takes some leadership from me to convince you that it ought to be done or you ought to do it.
We started to build Jersey Street.
And we had already built the street on the west side of the campus by the railroad.
And to get specific with you, we'd made it 57 feet wide.
And it proved very shortly that it was too narrow.
It congested when it parked along it.
It just wasn't wide enough.
You had no room for left turn movements.
So it was under design.
We made a mistake.
We started to build Jersey Street.
We designed it to have a 16-foot common left turn meeting, four running lanes, and two parking lanes.
And Mr.
Rudder never fell out of his chair when he saw what we had, because it was going to take part of his soccer field and part of the golf course.
And he said, no way.

says go back and do some figuring so we went back then we didn't do any more figuring we just let it rest a while went back to him and told him that we had come up with the idea that we were not we were not excessive in our design and that we felt like that's where it would be built and he said what about this street over here I said well it's too narrow I was used to making two mistakes
But he still didn't like it, and he said, go back and think about it again.
So we went back and pondered a while, and finally he called me and said, what do you think?
And I said, well, Mr. Rutter, I am not going to be a party to making the same mistake twice.
And I said, now, we've got the money for this.
The highway department's ready to let the contract.
And I think we're depriving the people of a facility
But I would not recommend to the Highway Department to do the same thing we did before.
His question to me is, have you been talking to some of my Board of Regents?
And I said, well, certainly not.
Why?
He said, well, none of my Board of Regents told me at the last meeting, when you build Jersey Street, don't let them build it too narrow.
Well, I won the battle with the help of somebody.

man when he was when he had his headset it was difficult because he was a strong leader and he had his own ideas but I've met with him on lots of occasions lots of occasions and we were we were pretty much of the same mind he was progressive and wanted his money spent well didn't want to throw it away and of course I felt the same way sure but uh
He was headstrong.
He had his firm convictions.
Of course, I admire a man with convictions.
That gets us to the next question.
What was your opinion of him as a person?
I thought he was fantastic.
I thought he was, well, of course, he was the most intimate president of A&M that I was ever socialized.
I mean, my relations were intimate.
I knew more of him, I dealt with him more, but I thought he was, I thought he did more for A&M than anybody before or after.
I'm talking about because of the length of time he was there and the amount of changes made.
I was a great admirer of his.
I think he was a successful leader in both military and in this institution and I think
Without question, he, I'll use the word, he fooled many of those people who were responsible for putting him in that position.
Yeah, how did that come?
Do you know anything about that?
Only what I read, and that is that they figured he'd smoothly glide the boat along, wouldn't rock it, you know, and wouldn't upset anything, but I was mistaken about him.
Well, was there a reasoning problem
firing President Miller, it appears that the board pretty much rules the university.
And when they saw these changes coming under General Rutter, why do you think?
Do you think he was just too powerful?
Why do you think that they gave him so much latitude
And here again, I've just got to quote Joe Hanover, but I think they were pleased with what he was doing.
Now that's the only answer I could have.
You know, otherwise they probably wouldn't tolerate it.
And some of the subsequent ones, they must not have been pleased with what was going on.
But it was...
getting too powerful, or whether it was didn't like the way it was administered, or just what, because they had that authority.
And it's very evident to me that they must have been pleased with with John Rutter, because I don't think anybody's too powerful for him to take whatever action they see fit.
Now, that's pure speculation.
Finally,

During this interview, we've examined early years, your education, your military career, both in active duty and the reserves, a lot of ideas and opinions that you've had about the military of Texas and on the leadership.
We must have left out somewhere along the line some important issues that you'd like to discuss or opinions or any other aspects of your life, have we?
Well, I guess inadvertently we may have, but I'm not real sure that I could start out and enumerate a lot of things.
I just look back on both my military career and my civilian career and attribute my training at Texas A&M
to a large degree for the success of both of them.
I started my military career there.
I started my civilian engineer career there.
I think I had teachers and associates in both aspects that I have a great deal of respect for.
I think we're

largely responsible for motivating me into doing the things that I needed to do to get a good basic education in both I think once I got out and began to hit some of life's problems I I look back there to to really see you know what the
what the foundation was.
Of course, World War II coming along took us to a completely different vocation very shortly.
I think the fact that I did have good training at A&M could very well be the reason I'm here today.
I think it taught me self-preservation.
I think it taught me
respect for my fellow man.
I think it taught me my responsibilities to the civilian world, to the military world, to my family, to my generations coming behind me.
I think all these things are started to ferment and grow right there at Texas A&M.
I had a man at Command General Staff, a man
Colonel at the Command General Staff School that made a comment one time that has really stuck with me.
We were just sitting around bullying one night in an off session and somebody asked him, Colonel Bones said, we get out of school, how are we going to know what we learned in this place?
And Command General Staff is the school for
higher commanders and staffs at Fort Leavenworth, you had so much stuff that was taught to you, so many leadership courses, so many tactics, you know, the gamut, just cram and cram and cram.
He said, when you get through, even though you've passed examinations and you've passed critiques and all this, he says, when we get back home, how are we going to know what we learned at this place?
And he said, when the problem arises and you find the solution to it, he says, you began to think a little bit, where did I learn this?
Or where did I get the background to make this decision?
He says, I think you'll remember that it was talked about at Fort Lattenworth.
And you know, that has really stuck in my mind.
And I have analyzed that a great many times after I'd
find a solution to some kind of problem.
I think, where did I learn that?
Or who gave me the idea to do this?
And I think that's a real good lesson in things where you have an opportunity to mingle with fellow man and go to school or study or research.
It doesn't really do you any good right then.
But you store it away.
And one of these days you have to make a decision, problem arises, and looking for the answer.
It's interesting to think back, where did I learn this?
Or how did I decide this course of action?
And he really gave me something to think about that day.
I wish more people would think back on and try to analyze things in their life.
Sure.
It would mean my job a lot more.
Yeah.
I thought it was a terrific answer.
And it did.
When we got out of school up there, you know, I'm not sure if somebody had said, sit down there and write what all you learned up there.
Man, you couldn't have.
You mean at Fort Leavenworth?
Yeah.
When you got on?
Yeah.
You couldn't have.
You could have maybe covered a cigarette paper or something like that.
But, oh, it must have, you know, the stuff that you stored away there that you recalled when the time came, it made it a terrific learning process.
and I tried to remember that all these subsequent schools and seminars that I was privileged to go to and as you say I went to a whole lot of them.

What another question along these lines then let's say you would have gone to another university now of course this is all hypothetical but if you would have gone to another university do you feel that
You would have had this training where you could make these decisions.
